Use ZML Instead License
=======================

Version 0.1 — the “please use ZML in production” edition

This repository is a fork and experimental offshoot of ZML. It is maintained
for private use, research, prototyping, benchmarking, and the occasional
conversation with a compiler that insists it knows better. It is not intended
to be a competing commercial product, a replacement for ZML, or a stealth
attempt to win a framework popularity contest.

The purpose of this framework is agent-assisted experimentation: humans set
the direction, agents help explore the design space, and the resulting code is
used to test ideas against reality. “It compiled” is not the same as “it was a
good idea,” and a benchmark with a suspiciously convenient denominator is not
the same as a scientific breakthrough. We therefore expect this repository to
contain experiments, dead ends, temporary scaffolding, sharp edges, and the
occasional surprisingly useful accident.

Why Rust?
---------

We love Zig. This choice is not a rejection of Zig, nor a declaration that one
language has defeated another in single combat. Zig is evolving quickly, which
is part of its charm and part of the churn. ZML is also evolving across many
moving parts. Rust gives this particular experiment a comparatively settled
foundation while we investigate ownership, runtime boundaries, compiler
integration, and other ideas that are easier to study when the floor stays in
roughly the same place.

The experiment is about learning, not language tribalism. If Zig is the right
tool for a problem, we will say so. If Rust is the right tool for a different
problem, we will say that too. The semicolons are not the point.

Relationship with ZML
---------------------

We are not affiliated with ZML, its maintainers, or any organization behind
it. We are not competitors either: ZML is the upstream project and the project
whose approach we admire most. We love the way ZML thinks about this space,
which is precisely why this private fork exists—to explore adjacent ideas
without adding every experiment, abstraction, or half-baked hypothesis to ZML
while it is still warm.

When an experiment here demonstrates a worthwhile gain—whether in clarity,
correctness, portability, performance, tooling, or simply a reduction in
headaches—we intend to document it and, where appropriate, submit the useful
parts to ZML or discuss them with its maintainers. A good result should travel
upstream. A bad result should at least stay here and serve as a warning to the
next curious person.

